In Shia holy cities such as Qom, there have been instances of pilgrims kissing and even licking the walls of mosques. Some religious leaders believe mosques in places such as Qom have a healing effect, and have even called on pilgrims to resist the epidemic.



Iran's Ministry of Health Statistics March 4, Iran, 586 new cases of coronary pneumonia, an additional 15 deaths. As of noon local time, a total of 2922 cases of new pneumonia were confirmed in Iran, of which 552 recovered and 92 died.

Iranian media said Reza Rahmani, the Minister of Industry, mining and trade, had been diagnosed with new pneumonia and was being treated in the ICU ward of a Tehran Hospital, Arabian Peninsula reported.

But industry officials denied the claim, saying that Lahamani was not infected with the new coronavirus but was treated for "chemical damage" in the IranIraq War.

Since the outbreak, more than Iranian political officials have been confirmed infected, including Vice President Abtekar and the head of the emergency health services.

As of March 3,23 members of Iran's parliament have been diagnosed, accounting for 8% of the total number of members. Abdolreza Mesri, the deputy speaker of parliament, has called on lawmakers to avoid contact with the public for the time being.

Iranian President Rohani said the outbreak of the new coronavirus has affected almost all Iranian provinces, the official website of the Iranian Presidential Palace reported Thursday.

As the outbreak continued to spread, Iran's supreme leader, Ali Khamenei Tuesday, issued a call for full cooperation with the Ministry of Health and urged the public to comply with outbreak protection regulations.

"Allah holds US accountable for our own health and that of others, " Ali Khamenei said, and "it is a good thing" to help stop the spread of the disease, and "evil" to do anything to encourage it.

In recent days, pilgrims have kissed and even licked the walls of mosques in Qom and other Shiite holy cities in an attempt to prove that religious sites are immune to the virus. Some religious leaders believe mosques in places such as Qom have a healing effect, and have even called on pilgrims to resist the epidemic.

Tuesday, two men were arrested for posting a video on the Internet showing them licking the walls of a mosque.

Last week, Saudi Arabia announced a temporary ban on pilgrims visiting the holy cities of Mecca and Medina.

But there are still large numbers of pilgrims in places such as Qom and mosques are still open. Already people are using the Internet to call for Ayatollah, the highest ranking Shia religious scholar, to intervene to prevent mosques from becoming a place of cross contamination. Ali Khamenei's a ayatollah, too.

According to the interface news reported earlier, in order to control the epidemic, many cities in Iran are urgently building the new coronavirus infection hospital. In the central city of Yazd, the government has promised to build a 1,000 sq m hospital within days. In Qom, the Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution also built a field hospital.

The Iranian food and Drug Administration announced that pharmacies would no longer be allowed to sell protective masks, which would be distributed free of charge to the public through government agencies. Priority will be given to the provinces affected by the outbreak.

SORENA Sattari, Iran's vice-president for science and technology, says production is now around 200,000 masks a day, and will rise to 300,000 a day.

Tehran's Bakiathalai Medical University on Wednesday announced the start of a clinical trial of a herbal medicine and a spray.

President Ali-Reza Jalali said the two drugs were not specifically designed to treat the new coronavirus, but were complementary to help patients recover more quickly. It takes at least two to three months from clinical trial to market approval.
